t-in-the-middle approach for large free variable spaces.\n   200→ * Split free variables into two halves, enumerate each half,\n   201→ * and combine to find optimal solution.\n   202→ */\n   203→function solveWithMITM(\n   204→  matrix: number[][],\n   205→  pivotCol: number[],\n   206→  pivotRow: number[],\n   207→  freeVars: number[],\n   208→  nButtons: number,\n   209→  mod: number\n   210→): number[] | null {\n   211→  const nFree = freeVars.length;\n   212→  const halfA = Math.floor(nFree / 2);\n   213→  const halfB = nFree - halfA;\n   214→\n   215→  // For each half, compute: for each assignment of free vars in that half,\n   216→  // what's the partial contribution to each pivot variable.\n   217→  // We also track the free variable values themselves and their partial sum.\n   218→\n   219→  // For the first half (freeVars[0..halfA-1]):\n   220→  // partial_pivot[i] = sum of matrix[pivotRow][freeVars[f]] * assignment[f] for f in first half\n   221→  // For the second half, similarly.\n   222→  // Full pivot value: matrix[row][cols] - partial_A - partial_B\n   223→\n   224→  // The sum of the solution = sum(freeAssignment values) + sum(pivot variable values)\n   225→  // pivot variable values depend on both halves.\n   226→\n   227→  // This is complex for general mod. For mod=2, it's XOR-based.\n   228→  // Let's implement for mod=2.\n   229→\n   230→  if (mod !== 2) {\n   231→    // Fallback: if we somehow get here with mod != 2 and huge space,\n   232→    // try a greedy approach: set free variables to 0.\n   233→    // This won't be optimal but handles edge cases.\n   234→    const solution: number[] = new Array(nButtons).fill(0);\n   235→    for (let i = 0; i < pivotCol.length; i++) {\n   236→      solution[pivotCol[i]] = matrix[i][nButtons]; // The augmented column\n   237→    }\n   238→    return solution;\n   239→  }\n   240→\n   241→  // For mod=2, represent contributions as bit vectors.\n   242→  // For each pivot variable i, the contribution from